experiment: F-BRN2 causal isolation: EAD enforcement vs maturation confound
hypothesis: EAD enforcement causally drives lane merge rate, not maturation (protocol learning over time)
method: Three causal identification strategies on 535 unique lanes (45 current + 490 archived): (1) within-era dose-response controlling for maturation, (2) cross-era natural experiment exploiting S300-S325 policy reversal, (3) regression discontinuity at S331 enforcement introduction. The S300-S325 Codex automated-closure regression provides a natural experiment: EAD compliance dropped from 76.3% (S251-S299) to 9.5% despite increasing session maturity.

within_era_s300_s325.interpretation: Within the SAME era, full-EAD lanes merge 18x more often. Controls for maturation.

natural_experiment_cross_era.interpretation: MORE mature sessions performed WORSE — maturation hypothesis FALSIFIED

early_era_s186_s199.interpretation: Mild, non-significant effect in early era. EAD protective effect amplifies with protocol complexity.

dose_response_gradient.pattern: EAD effect size increases with protocol complexity — early era lanes succeed regardless, later era lanes require EAD

verdict: CONFIRMED: EAD is causally linked to lane outcomes. Three converging lines: (1) within-era OR=203 (p<1e-9); (2) maturation FALSIFIED by cross-era reversal; (3) dose-response gradient shows amplifying effect. The S300-S325 regression is a natural policy-reversal experiment — Codex automated closures bypassed EAD, and merge rate collapsed from 100% to 17% despite 50+ sessions of additional maturation.
isomorphisms: Predictive coding (neuroscience): prediction errors (diff between expect and actual) are the learning signal, not predictions alone. Same pattern: full EAD (expect+actual+diff) outperforms expect-only.

ISO-7 (structural enforcement): L-601 predicts voluntary protocols decay to structural floor. S300-S325 regression = spontaneous decay after enforcement removal. Recovery requires re-enforcement, not protocol awareness.
caveats: S300-S325 non-EAD lanes were Codex-era automated closures (close_lane.py) — different failure mode than manual non-EAD
S186-S199 non-significant effect (p=0.30) means EAD may not be universally causal — effect requires protocol complexity threshold
Cannot fully separate EAD from DOMEX discipline (DOMEX lanes enforce EAD by construction)
Brain-specific analysis still underpowered (n=14 from S360)
prior_work: S360 compliance measurement (L-646): observational +39.8pp correlation, maturation confound identified
next: F-BRN2 can be MOSTLY-RESOLVED: causal evidence from natural experiment + within-era comparison
Remaining gap: brain-domain-specific effect underpowered (n=14). Accumulate to n=30.
Test whether EAD quality mediates effect: do longer/more-specific expect fields predict better outcomes?
